-md-12 gf_col-sm-12 gf_col-xs-12" id="c-1625751610245" data-id="1625751610245"><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1627477816449" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1627477816449"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs gf-elm-left-lg" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p>Magnesium, Methylation, and the MTHFR Gene</p></div></div><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" data-atomgroup="element" id="e-1658631405139" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1658631405139"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left" data-gemlang="en"><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Magnesium is essential for the proper functioning of numerous processes within the body. As a cofactor for more than 300 enzymatic reactions, it is involved in muscle contraction, neuromuscular pathways, glucose maintenance, heart contraction, and blood pressure regulation.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Magnesium is also essential for energy production, nucleic acid synthesis, bone development, and the active transmembrane transport of other ions (i.e., the movement of molecules across cell membranes using ATP).</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">Above all, magnesium is a vital cofactor in the methylation cycle, and its deficiency may contribute to other MTHFR-related symptoms.</span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></span></p><p dir="ltr" style="line-height:1.2;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:10pt;"><span style="font-size:11pt;font-family:Arial;color:#000000;background-color:transparent;font-weight:400;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;text-decoration:none;vertical-align:baseline;white-space:pre;white-space:pre-wrap;">This article will discuss the body’s needs for magnesium and its role in methylation. We will explain how to identify and correct a magnesium deficiency and why this is so important for those with an MTHFR gene mutation.</span></p><p><span id="docs-internal-guid-20428221-7fff-e060-ac6f-d0831767b43e"></span><br class="Apple-interchange-newline"></p></div></div><div data-label="Heading" data-key="heading" id="e-1632414828158" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-heading" data-ver="1" data-id="1632414828158"><div class="elm text-edit gf